**ABSTRACT**

N-nitroso-N-methylurea (NMU) is a potent carcinogenic agent that induces significant oxidative stress and nephrotoxicity in experimental models. _Pleurotus ostreatus_, commonly known as oyster mushroom, possesses demonstrated antioxidant properties. This study investigated the nephroprotective effects of _P. ostreatus_ ethanolic extract against NMU-induced kidney damage in _Mus musculus_. Twenty-five (25) female mice were randomly assigned to four experimental groups: control (distilled water), cisplatin treatment, and two _P. ostreatus_ extract groups (200 mg/kg and 400 mg/kg). Following NMU induction, animals received treatments for nine weeks. Body weight was monitored weekly, and kidney antioxidant parameters including catalase (CAT), superoxide dismutase (SOD), reduced glutathione (GSH), glutathione peroxidase (GPx), malondialdehyde (MDA), and protein content were assessed using standard biochemical assays. Mice treated with _P. ostreatus_ extract demonstrated dose-dependent protective effects. The 400 mg/kg group showed significantly higher body weight gain throughout the study period compared to control and cisplatin groups. Kidney antioxidant assessment revealed that the 400 mg/kg group exhibited significantly reduced lipid peroxidation (MDA: 1.836 ± 0.11 nmol/ml vs. control 1.966 ± 0.07 nmol/ml) and better preservation of glutathione levels (GSH: 9.712 ± 0.26 µmol/ml vs. control 11.888 ± 0.37 µmol/ml, p≤0.001). While SOD activity decreased across all NMU-treated groups (79.745 ± 1.10 vs. control 90.052 ± 1.74, p≤0.001), catalase activity was better preserved in the 200 mg/kg group compared to cisplatin treatment. Protein content remained stable across all groups. _Pleurotus ostreatus_ ethanolic extract exhibits significant dose-dependent nephroprotective and antioxidant properties against NMU-induced kidney damage. The extract effectively reduced oxidative stress markers, particularly lipid peroxidation, and partially preserved glutathione-dependent antioxidant systems. These findings support its potential therapeutic application as an adjuvant in conditions involving oxidative kidney injury, warranting further scientific and translational research.

**CHAPTER ONE**

**INTRODUCTION**

Medicinal plants have been utilized as herbal remedies from the beginning of human history, both as nutritional supplements and in the treatment and management of a variety of ailments, including cancer (Imtiaz et al., 2024). According to the World Health Organization, medicinal plants are compounds that possess bioactive properties that can be used for therapeutic purposes or have the potential to produce metabolites for the formulation of effective drugs (WHO, 2023). Prior to the 20th century, medicinal plant products accounted for around 80% of all medications used to treat various ailments (Newman and Cragg, 2016). Many well-known traditional medical practices have emerged as a result of the development of plant-based medicinal systems, including Ayurveda and Unani in the Indian subcontinent, Traditional Chinese Medicine in China, and various indigenous healing systems in Africa, North America, and South America (Patwardhan et al., 2023). These systems show a thorough comprehension of the pharmacological characteristics of plants and their integration into integrated health practices, highlighting the role that cultural environment plays in the development of medical knowledge (Dahiya and Banerjee, 2016; Dekebo, 2019). A significant section of the world's population relies on medicinal plants as their main source of healthcare. In emerging countries, where the need for these resources is rising, this dependence is noticeably more pronounced. This reliance highlights how essential medicinal plants are to traditional medical procedures (Dekebo, 2019; Shukla, 2023).

A plant is considered medicinal if it contains substances that can be used therapeutically or as building blocks for the semi-synthesis of medicines. Tannins, flavonoids, saponins, alkaloids, and glycosides are examples of these substances (Adeboye et al., 2025). The bioactive substances found in medicinal plants, such as phenolics, flavonoids, tannins, alkaloids, terpenes, and saponins, are the main cause of their abundance in natural antioxidants (Cavazos et al., 2021). Secondary metabolites, particularly phenolics and flavonoids, have powerful antioxidant capabilities that scavenge reactive oxygen species (ROS) and reactive nitrogen species (RNS). These systems help to mitigate oxidative stress-related illnesses like cancer, rheumatism, chronic bronchitis, asthma, renal failure, diabetes, aging, and neurological disorders (Pham-Huy et al., 2008). Furthermore, they can operate as reducing agents and metal chelators (Kasote et al., 2015). Therefore, it is essential to examine the antioxidant activity of these plants in order to determine their pharmacological efficiency against different disorders. However, choosing a suitable approach to assess antioxidant capacity is crucial. 2,2-di-phenyl-1-picrylhydrazyl (DPPH), 2,2′-azinobis-(3-ethylbenzothiazoline-6-sulfonic) acid (ABTS), and ferric-reducing antioxidant power (FRAP) are the most often used assays to assess the antioxidant capacity of plant extracts (Chaves et al., 2020).

This emerging sector is consistent with the global trend toward natural health solutions, stressing eco-friendly methods and lowering dependency on synthetic pharmaceuticals. Plant-derived medicines provide considerable prospects for economic growth and health improvement in biodiversity-rich poor nations. By exploiting their natural resources, these nations may stimulate local research and development, leading to creative healthcare solutions, as evidenced by a study undertaken by (Chaachouay and Zidane, 2024; Obahiagbon and Ogwu, 2024).

The use of natural products for primary healthcare have grown in popularity worldwide over the last decade (Bareetseng, 2022). The global market for medicinal plants and plant-derived drugs was estimated to be worth 25.6 billion dollars in 2015, and is expected to reach 35.4 billion dollars in 2020 (Alonso-Castro et al., 2017). This clearly indicates that the consumption of medicinal plants is a current topic of interest. However, there is little scientific proof of the toxicity, chemical makeup, and pharmacological effects of many medicinal plants (Alonso-Castro et al., 2018).

**1.1 Some Important Medicinal Plants**

**1.1.1 _Medicago sativa_**

A member of the _Fabaceae_ family, _Medicago sativa_ (alfalfa) has a variety of uses, including as an aperient, antiscorbutic, oxytocic, diuretic, haemostatic, stimulant, nutritive, and tonic (Gazel et al., 2023). Medicago sativa is a significant medicinal plant used in traditional medicine systems to treat problems with the digestive system, the central nervous system, diabetes. asthma. inflammation, gallstones, kidney problems, and microbial infections (Rani et al., 2024). Medicago leaves are rich in vitamin K which is used medicinally to stimulate blood clotting. This plant is valuable in the treatment of jaundice (Bora and Sharma, 2011).

**1.1.2 _Momordica charantia_**

_Momordica charantia_ (bitter melon), from the _Cucurbitaceae_ family, is traditionally used in many tropical and subtropical cultures to manage diabetes, gastrointestinal disorders, and infections. Recent phytochemical screening of methanolic leaf extracts revealed alkaloids, flavonoids, saponins, glycosides, tannins, steroids, and terpenoids, which contribute to antibacterial and antioxidant effects (Giwa et al., 2024). These bioactive compounds support its use as a natural remedy for bacterial infections and metabolic disorders, and the plant remains an important candidate for further drug discovery.

**1.1.3** **_Curcuma longa_**

_Curcuma longa_ (turmeric), from the _Zingiberaceae_ family, is widely known for its anti‑inflammatory and antioxidant properties. Curcumin, the major bioactive compound, has demonstrated immune‑modulating, anti‑inflammatory, and potential anticancer activities in various studies. Its traditional use spans treatment of pain, inflammatory disorders, digestive problems, and skin conditions. Modern pharmacological research continues to investigate curcumin's therapeutic potential in chronic conditions characterized by inflammation and oxidative stress (Olaniyan et al., 2023).

**1.1.4** **_Zingiber officinale_**

_Zingiber officinale_ (ginger), another member of the _Zingiberaceae_ family, is widely used in traditional medicine for its digestive, anti‑nausea, and anti‑inflammatory properties. Recent studies combining in vitro antimicrobial assays and molecular docking have identified compounds such as shogaol and hexahydrocurcumin with potential antibacterial effects against _E. coli_, suggesting promise for ginger in managing bacterial infections (Buru, 2025). Its rich content of gingerols, shogaols, and other phenolic compounds also underpins its antioxidant and anti‑inflammatory benefits, supporting its continued relevance in nutraceutical development.

**1.1.5** **_Ocimum sanctum_**

_Ocimum sanctum_ (holy basil), from the _Lamiaceae_ family, is widely used in Ayurvedic and African traditional medicine for treating respiratory disorders, stress, fever, and gastrointestinal discomfort. Its leaves contain eugenol, ursolic acid, rosmarinic acid, and flavonoids that contribute to its antioxidant, anti-inflammatory, immunomodulatory, and antimicrobial effects (Jamshidi and Cohen, 2017; Patel and Gupta, 2022). Recent studies highlight its adaptogenic properties and suggest potential benefits in metabolic and inflammatory diseases (Patel and Gupta, 2022).

**1.1.6 _Echinacea purpuream_**

_Echinacea purpurea_ (coneflower), of the _Asteraceae_ family, is commonly used to support the immune system and reduce the duration of upper respiratory infections. Multiple clinical trials and recent meta-analyses indicate modest benefits in preventing or shortening common colds, likely via immune modulation by polysaccharides and alkamides. Contemporary reviews emphasize standardization of extract composition and dosing to improve reproducibility across studies (Gancitano et al., 2024).

**1.1.7** **_Centella asiatica_**

Centella asiatica (gotu kola), of the _Apiaceae_ family, is traditionally used for wound healing, cognitive support, and circulatory disorders. Triterpenoids such as asiaticoside, madecassoside and their aglycones mediate wound-healing, neuroprotective, and anti-inflammatory activities, which are supported by a growing body of preclinical and clinical evidence. Recent reviews stress improved extraction technologies and evidence for skin and cognitive indications, while advocating standardized formulations for clinical translation (Hein et al., 2025).

**1.1.8** **_Camellia sinensis_**

Camellia sinensis (green tea), of the _Theaceae_ family, is widely consumed for general health and used traditionally for digestive and metabolic complaints. Its biological activities are primarily attributed to catechins, especially epigallocatechin gallate (EGCG), which display antioxidant, anti-inflammatory, and chemopreventive properties. Systematic reviews and meta-analyses support green tea's modest beneficial effects on oxidative stress markers and some metabolic endpoints, while emphasizing dose and preparation variability (Zhao et al., 2022).

**1.1.9** **_Andrographis paniculate_**

Andrographis paniculata, from the Acanthaceae family, is used traditionally for febrile and respiratory illnesses. Andrographolide and its derivatives are the principal bioactives, demonstrating anti-inflammatory, antiviral, and immunomodulatory effects in preclinical and clinical studies. Recent reviews highlight its utility in acute respiratory infections and as a promising lead for anti-inflammatory drug development, while calling for larger, well-controlled clinical trials (Intharuksa et al., 2022).

**1.2. Aim of The Study**

This study aims to investigate the antioxidant effects of _Pleurotus ostreatus_ on the kidneys of _Mus musculus_ exposed to Nitrosomethylurea (NMU). It focuses on determining whether the mushroom extract can reduce oxidative stress, protect kidney tissue, and improve markers of kidney function.

**1.3. Objectives of The Study**

- To determine the antioxidant potential of _Pleurotus ostreatus_ in NMU-induced kidney damage in _Mus musculus_.
- To assess changes in key oxidative stress and kidney function biomarkers following treatment with _Pleurotus ostreatus_ extract.
- To compare the renal protective outcomes between extract-treated groups and NMU-only control groups to determine the therapeutic relevance of _Pleurotus ostreatus_.

**CHAPTER TWO**

**LITERATURE REVIEW**

**2.1 Taxonomical Classification of _Pleurotus Ostreatus_**

The oyster mushroom, or _Pleurotus ostreatus_, is one of the most extensively grown edible mushrooms in the world. _Pleurotus ostreatus_ belongs to the kingdom Fungi and is classified under the division Basidiomycota. It is a member of the class Agaricomycetes and falls within the order Agaricales. The species is placed in the family Pleurotaceae under the genus _Pleurotus_, with the species name _ostreatus_ (Wright et al., 2023).

**2.1.1 Morphological Description of _Pleurotus Ostreatus_**

The fruiting body holds a cap (pileus) that ranges in diameter from 5.6 to 11.2 cm. It is white to grey in color and has a convex profile that develops into a characteristic shell-like shape. To the touch, the cap's surface seems silky and smooth (Kadam et al., 2024). The white gills of the hymenophore are widely decurrent and run the length of the stipe. Under a microscope, the spores have an oblong to cylindrical shape and look whitish to lilac grey when seen in large quantities. The stipe has a smooth, cream-colored appearance and is 4.7 to 7.2 cm long and 1.3 to 2.2 cm in diameter. When handled, the specimen emits a faint, nondescript odor (Kadam et al., 2024). The morphological characteristics of _Pleurotus ostreatus_, including its distinctive fruiting body structure, are illustrated in Figure 1.

**Figure 1:** _Pleurotus ostreatus_ showing the Fruiting body

**Source**: Federal Institute of Industrial Research (2025)

Mushrooms are recognized as functional foods with health benefits that extend beyond their nutritional value (Lysakowska et al., 2023). Among the numerous edible mushrooms, species within the Pleurotus genus produce significant amounts of unique mycochemicals (Cateni et al., 2022). Several Pleurotus species are now widely cultivated because of their high mineral content, therapeutic properties, short life cycle, efficient recycling of agricultural and industrial wastes, and minimal resource and technical requirements (Raman et al., 2021).

The substrates used in cultivating Pleurotus mushrooms are also valuable as organic fertilizers and soil conditioners that enhance plant growth. Fermented wastes from mushroom cultivation can serve as animal feed, thereby addressing waste management challenges while providing economic and environmental benefits (Owaid et al., 2017). Numerous studies worldwide confirm that Pleurotus mushrooms are highly nutritious and contain diverse bioactive compounds, including terpenoids, steroids, phenols, alkaloids, lectins, and nucleotides. These compounds, isolated from fruiting bodies, mycelia, and culture broths, exhibit promising biological activities (Zhou et al., 2024).

_Pleurotus ostreatus_ has a high-water content and a low calorific value (105-209 J per 100 g-1). The median calorific value of a cultivated species of _P. ostreatus_ is 151 J per 100 g of edible portion (Aubrey et al., 2022). Fungal scent compounds offer foods made with mushrooms a distinct taste and increase hunger, although they have little nutritional significance. There are over 150 distinct types of aromatic chemicals found in mushrooms. Octavalent carbonate alcohols and carbonyl compounds, such as 1-octanol, 3-octanol, 3-octanon, 1-caprynol-3-ol, 1-octynol-3-ol, 2-octynol-3-ol, and 1-caprynol-3-on, are primarily responsible for the scent of the majority of edible mushrooms. Compound 1-octynol-3-ol predominates in _P. ostreatus_ fructifications due to its existence (Lilechi, 2016). The amount of amino acids, nucleotides, nitrogen, phosphorus, potassium, sulfur, iron, zinc, and the autoxidation of unsaturated fatty acids all affect the mushroom's scent (Jiang et al., 2023). _P. ostreatus_ is the second most significant mushroom that is grown for food in the world. (Raman et al., 2021). In terms of nutrition, it has a distinct flavor and aromatic qualities and is said to be low in fat and high in protein, fiber, carbs, minerals, and vitamins (Sethi et al., 2022). The nutritional components of commercially grown mushrooms are comparable to those found in wild varieties. However, the strain, origin, extraction method, and growth circumstances all affect the qualitative and quantitative variations in the chemical makeup of _P. ostreatus_ products (Siwulski et al., 2025).

About 100 distinct bioactive compounds are found in the fruiting body of _P. ostreatus_, and these chemicals are primarily thought to represent a possible new source of dietary fiber. Fungal cell walls, on the other hand, are abundant in non-starch polysaccharides, of which β-glucan is the most intriguing functional component. Phenolic compounds, such as protocatechuic acid, gallic acid, homogentisic acid, rutin, myrictin, chrysin, naringin, and tocopherol, including α-tocopherol and γ-tocopherol, ascorbic acid, and β-carotene, each of which have exceptional medical benefits (Sztupecki et al., 2023). Moreover, they are healthy foods, rich in protein, lipids, carbohydrates, vitamin and minerals content but low in calories and fat content (Table 1).

The potential of mushrooms as a source of new proteins is quickly gaining recognition. Numerous proteins with distinct characteristics have been identified, such as hydrophobins, lignocellulolytic enzymes, lectins, and protease inhibitors (Scholtmeijer et al., 2023). They can provide answers to a number of biotechnological and medical issues, including low agricultural yields, microbial drug resistance, and the need for renewable energy. On the other hand, the industrial use and large-scale synthesis of some fungal proteins demonstrate their biotechnological potential and position higher fungi as a viable, if mostly untapped, source of distinctive proteins (Tiwari and Park, 2024). Although mushrooms contain a wide variety of proteins, only few of these proteins have been discovered and even fewer have been described. On the other hand, strains, physical and chemical variations in the growth media, substrate composition, pileus size, and harvest time have all been found to affect the amount of protein in _P. ostreatus_ (Gebru et al., 2024). However, some _Pleurotus sp._ mushrooms have complete proteins with a good distribution of essential and non-essential amino acids, especially GABA, which functions as a neurotransmitter, and ornithine, which is a precursor in the synthesis of arginine. As a result, the proteins from these mushrooms are of superior quality (Table 2).

Compared to carbohydrates and proteipn, edible Pleurotus mushrooms have a relatively low-fat content. The majority of the fat in mushrooms is made up of unsaturated fatty acids. Oleic acid is the primary monounsaturated fatty acid (F.A.) in _P. ostreatus_, while linoleic acid is the primary polyunsaturated F.A. _P. ostreatus_ has a fat content of between 0.2 and 8 g per 100 g of dried fruit bodies. (Lesa et al., 2022).

Mushrooms contain a variety of carbohydrates, such as starches, pentoses, hexoses, disaccharides, amino sugars, sugar alcohols, and sugar acids. Dietary fiber and carbs are abundant in _P. ostreatus_ mushrooms. Chitin and partly digestible polysaccharides make up the crude digestible fiber component of the mushroom (Manikandan, 2020). _P. ostreatus_ mostly contains carbohydrates in the form of polysaccharides, which include a variety of substances such as monosaccharides and their derivatives; oligosaccharides are also known as soluble sugars (Gupta et al., 2019). Additionally, they are represented by glycogen, which contains a variety of glycosidic linkages, including branching (1-3), (1-6)-β-glucans, and linear (1-3)-α-glucans. _P. ostreatus_ mushrooms have a dietary fiber level of 4.1 g per 100 g of edible portions (Megersa and Tolessa, 2024).

Trace elements have significant physiological effects on several organs and cellular processes, making them vital for human health. Fruit bodies of mushrooms are high in vitamins, primarily B1, B2, C, and D2 (Noreen et al., 2025). In addition to other vitamins including ergosterol, biotin, phytochinon, and tocopherols, group B vitamins are rich, especially thamine, riboflavin, pyridoxine, pantotene acid, nicotinic acid, nicotinamid, folic acid, and cobalamin (Effiong et al., 2024). _P. ostreatus_ has more folacine, vitamin B1, vitamin B3, and less vitamin B12 than other mushroom species. The vitamin content (mostly vitamin B complex) of _P. ostreatus_ mushroom shown in (Table 3).

The enzymatic activity of diverse mushroom species varies, with _P. ostreatus_ having greater activity of the polyphenoloxidase molecule. This enzyme works by catalyzing phenol component oxidation, resulting in a quick darkening of harvested mushrooms, which decreases their sensory and nutritional characteristics. Conversely, product darkness reduces maintaining quality and hence market value (Murniati et al., 2018).

Over time, there has been a growing interest in ingesting mushrooms to correct or treat a wide range of serious conditions around the world (Usman et al., 2021). _P. ostreatus_ is the best example of a food mushroom with strong therapeutic characteristics and pharmacological potential. Mushrooms have been utilized for medicinal purposes in China since 100 AD (Waktola and Temesgen, 2020). Mushrooms have long been extensively established for their therapeutic benefits, especially in Eastern Asian nations (Ray et al., 2024). Numerous studies conducted over the past several decades have demonstrated their positive benefits on health and the management of certain diseases. Figure 2 summarizes the many bioactive components of mushrooms that may have therapeutic and health-promoting properties (Lu et al., 2025). Approximately 6% to 10% of edible oyster mushrooms are known to have therapeutic qualities, and these qualities have led to their utilization as significant natural components in the manufacturing of pharmaceutical goods. Furthermore, _P. ostreatus_ mushrooms are particularly well-liked because of its therapeutic abilities and traditional medicinal qualities (Sreedharan et al., 2025). In addition to being utilized as functional foods, mushrooms have been shown to have anti-oxidant, anti-inflammatory, anti-carcinogenic, anti-microbial, anti-bacterial, anti-fungal, anti-diabetic, anti-angiogenic, immune modulatory, hepatoprotective, hypoglycemic, anti-viral, anti-tumor, anti-hypercholesterolemic, anti-hypertensive, protecting the liver, promoting general fitness, anti-asthmatic, anti-obesity, anti-atherosclerotic, and anti-ulcer, besides being used as functional foods (Ferdousi et al., 2020). The medicinal and pharmacological importance of _P. ostreatus_ is illustrated in Figure 2 and Table 5. Researchers have shown that a number of edible and therapeutic mushrooms have substantial free-radical scavenging activity and inherent antioxidant qualities (Gupta et al., 2019). The ethanolic extract of dietary _Pleurotus ostreatus_ mushrooms has been shown to have anti-oxidant activity in vitro and in vivo by scavenging hydroxyl and superoxide radicals, inhibiting lipid peroxidation, acting as ferrous ion chelating agents, reducing ferric ion oxidation, and quenching 2,3-diazabicyclo. (Sreedharanet et al., 2025). Another investigation found that _Pleurotus ostreatus_ had enhanced antioxidant qualities because of the presence of a carbohydrate component (β-glucan), which appeared to be the cause of the antioxidant activity. Additionally, _Pleurotus ostreatus_ mushrooms are a high source of antioxidants for use as food additives in the food industry (Michalska et al., 2025).

A number of _Pleurotus ostreatus_ extracts have been demonstrated to have anti-carcinogenic properties. However, clinical and medical reports of anticancer activity have not confirmed it (Phonemany et al., 2025). According to research, _Pleurotus ostreatus_ extract can stop cancer cells from dividing by keeping them in the G0/G1 phase of the cell cycle. This effect is mediated by increased expression of tumor suppressor proteins, such as p53 and p21, which are involved in apoptosis and cell cycle regulation, respectively. Additionally, the regulation of retinoblastoma (Rb) protein phosphorylation is crucial for maintaining this cell cycle arrest (Sreedharan et al, 2025).

In colorectal adenocarcinoma and human monocytic leukemia cell lines, the _Pleurotus ostreatus_ extract causes reactive oxygen species generation and mitochondrial dysfunction. In this sense, the protein extract of _Pleurotus ostreatus_ might be regarded as a critical source of novel anticancer drugs. All types of edible mushrooms can help prevent prostate and breast cancer (Manikandan, 2020). _Pleurotus ostreatus_ has been utilized as a medication and nutraceutical to treat people with cancer. The anti-tumor effect of dietary mushrooms _Pleurotus ostreatus_ mycelia derived proteoglycans that increased the cytotoxicity of mouse natural killer cells, stimulated the production of nitric oxide by macrophages, and strongly interacted with the lectin concanavalin A (Con A), which is specific to glucose or mannose and indicates the presence of many terminal sugars with glucose and mannose (Kaushik and Kaur, 2025).

_Pleurotus ostreatus_ contains bioactive substances that have been linked to anti-tumor properties, such as glucans, ergosterol, amino acids (arginine and glutamine), and proteoglycans (Sreedharanet et al., 2025). The inhibition of neovascularization caused by tumor development in sarcoma 180 cells in vitro, T cell activation and clonal expansion, an increase in NK (natural killer cells) and THC (T helper cells), stimulation of interleukin synthesis, stimulation of immunological function, extension cell survival, and increased tolerance to chemotherapy are all potential mechanisms of action of these substances (Galappaththi et al., 2021). Through a variety of distinct modes of action, several _Pleurotus ostreatus_ extracts have demonstrated anticancer properties in various CCLs (cancer cell lines) and experimental animals. In human androgen-independent PC-3 (prostate cancer) cells, water-soluble extracts of _Pleurotus ostreatus_ showed the greatest cytotoxicity and caused apoptosis (Galappaththi et al., 2021). Mushrooms require antibacterial and antifungal substances to survive in their natural habitat (Gupta et al., 2019). Both Gram-positive and Gram-negative bacteria were susceptible to the antibacterial spectrum of Pleurotus species. The antimicrobial qualities of _Pleurotus ostreatus_ edible mushrooms' ethyl acetate extract against B. subtilis, S. aureus, E. coli, K. pneumonia, and Proteus vulgaris were examined. Additionally, _Pleurotus ostreatus_ demonstrated an efficient inhibitory zone against every pathogenic strain (Sutthisa and Anujakkawan, 2023). The antimicrobial and antifungal properties of oyster mushrooms are dependent on the kind of solvent, acetone extract, and ether extract against Gram-negative bacteria (Ahmed et al., 2022).

The macro-fungus extracted with petroleum was shown to inhibit both Gram-positive and Gram-negative bacteria tested in vitro, indicating that _Pleurotus ostreatus_ possesses broad-spectrum antibacterial activities (Yakobi et al., 2023). The phenolic and tannin components of _Pleurotus ostreatus_, a dietary mushroom, were found to have antibacterial properties similar to those of many medicinal plants, with mechanisms of action characterized by cell membrane lysis, proteolytic enzymes, microbial adhesion, and inhibition of protein synthesis. On the other hand, the organic extracts of this mushroom, methanol and chloroform, were found to be effective against Gram-positive bacteria, suggesting that they could be a potential source of antibacterial agents (Oda and Muhammed, 2024).

Anti-viral activity is documented for both entire extracts of dietary oyster mushrooms and isolated phytochemicals. Specific drugs are an emergency foundation needed for the cure of viral illnesses, which cannot be treated by standard antibiotics (Elhusseiny et al., 2022). They may act directly by blocking viral nucleic acid synthesis, adsorption, viral enzymes, and virus uptake in mammalian cells. Anti-viral actions are indirect because polysaccharides or other complex compounds stimulate the immune system (Islam et al., 2019). The aim of anti-viral chemotherapy is the discovery of anti-viral activity agents that are specific for the inhibition of viral multiplication without affecting normal cell division. It is also necessary to identify and develop new anti-viral agents without adverse side effects and viral resistance (Aw et al., 2025). A laccase has been purified from _Pleurotus ostreatus_, which is capable to inhibit the hepatitis C virus entry into peripheral blood cells, activity toward HIV-1 reverse transcriptase, and hepatoma HepG2 cells and its replication (Mominur et al., 2023). The medicinal properties and pharmacological potentiality of _Pleurotus ostreatus_ are shown in Table 5.

Dietary oyster mushrooms are an ideal food for the dietetic prevention of hyperglycemia due to their low-fat content, high dietary fiber, and protein (Manikandan, 2020). Hyperglycemia is an important characteristic of diabetes mellitus (DM). The dietary _Pleurotus ostreatus_ mushrooms were orally administered to alloxan-induced diabetic rats which revealed that the combination-produced synergistic effects have shown blood glucose-lowering effects in insulin-dependent and insulin-independent diabetic conditions. Moreover, several oral anti-diabetic drugs have been found in edible oyster mushrooms (Gupta et al., 2019). Hypothesized the anti-diabetic potential of _Pleurotus ostreatus_ in alloxan-induced diabetic mice, and the result of this research showed that the _Pleurotus ostreatus_ delivered a significant hypoglycemic effect in diabetic mice which is capable of progressing hyperlipidemia functions. Moreover, numerous researches showed the result of the treatment with a high level of _Pleurotus ostreatus_ extract could reduce the (HBGL) high blood glucose level in hyperglycemic rats (Lesa et al., 2022).

Nowadays, immuno-modulators are the most important medicinal mushroom drugs which are used particularly in Japan, Korea, China, and other East Asian countries (Gupta et al., 2019). Low cytotoxicity alone with immuno-modulatory activity raises the possibility which could be effective to build up immune resistance, in carcinogenic patients receiving conventional traditional treatment, chemotherapy, and decreased toxicity. Have also analyzed that a large number of compounds have been isolated from oyster mushrooms like lectins, polysaccharides (beta-glucans) (Manikandan, 2020). Polysaccharides-peptides, and polysaccharide-protein complex that have been found to have immuno-modulatory activity and these are suggested to enhance cellular components of the immune system (Li et al., 2025)

Nowadays, _Pleurotus ostreatus_ is one of the best sources of nutrients and medicinal resources since it contains several bioactive components that develop its large number of pharmacological effects. It contains the most common nutrients, i.e., carbohydrates, protein, amino acids, vitamins, and fatty acids. As well as, due to their high nutritional values and medicinal properties, they are considered a functional food and help to control many human ailments, including anti-oxidant, anti-inflammatory, anti-carcinogenic, anti-viral, anti-fungal, anti-bacterial, anti-diabetic, anti-angiogenic, immuno-modulatory, hypoglycemic, and hepatoprotective (Effiong et al., 2024). The blessings of _Pleurotus ostreatus_ mushrooms are particularly reasonable because they grew on some cheaper agricultural or woodland wastes such as wheat straw, rice straw, teff straw, paddy straw, corn cobs, cotton, waste, coffee pulp, and sugarcane bagasse (Faiq et al., 2025).

**CHAPTER THREE**

**MATERIALS AND METHOD**

**3.1 Materials**

**3.1.1 Plant Materials**

_Pleurotus ostreatus_ were gathered in June 2025 from the Federal Institute of Industrial Research's Oshodi Mushroom House. The mushrooms were identified and taxonomically validated at the Department of Botany, University of Lagos, Lagos, Nigeria, courtesy of Mr Nodza George, using voucher number LUH 100639 of the plants stored in the herbarium.

**3.1.2 Chemical Reagents**

N-nitroso-N-methylurea (NMU), Cisplatin, absolute ethanol, FBS (Fetal Bovine Serum), 0.9% Normal Saline

**3.1.3 Equipment and Supplies**

The experimental procedures required various laboratory materials and instruments, including EDTA bottles, heparin bottles, surgical blade, scapel, forceps, funnel, pins, masking tape, cannula, syringe, mice cage. Animal pellet feed, wood shavings, iron mesh, plastic cage, weighing balance, electric grinder, aluminium foil, cotton wool, bottom flask, jerry can, nitrile gloves, beaker, sterile bottles, muslin cloth, hot plate, dissecting board, saline water, distilled water.

**3.2 Experimental Animals**

For this study, twenty-five female albino mice weighing an average of 19-28 grams were obtained from the National Agency for Food and Drug Administration and Control (NAFDAC), Lagos, Nigeria. The mice were randomly divided into four groups of six and housed in well-aerated metal cages in the animal house of the Department of Cell Biology and Genetics, Faculty of Science, University of Lagos. The mice were kept under standard laboratory conditions at room temperature and maintained in cages lined with fresh sawdust bedding, which was replaced regularly to ensure a clean and comfortable environment throughout the study period. The mice were provided with normal pellet feed and water ad libitum for the duration of the experiment. Their weights were recorded using a sensitive weighing balance.

The mice were randomly divided into four experimental groups based on treatment regimen. The first group served as the control and received distilled water only. The second group received cisplatin and served as the positive control. The remaining two groups were administered Pleurotus ostreatus extract at doses of 200 mg kg⁻¹ and 400 mg kg⁻¹, respectively.

**3.3 Mushroom Preparation and Extraction**

_Pleurotus ostreatus_ was collected and dried at 35°C in a food dehydrator with circulation for two days to completely remove any remaining water molecules. The dehydrated _Pleurotus ostreatus_ was ground in a stainless grinder machine to produce a fine powdered version of the mushroom. The mushroom extracts were prepared using a crude extraction process with a solute-to-solvent ratio of 1:3, i.e., 1g of powdered _Pleurotus ostreatus_ soaked in 3ml of ethanol to produce a well soaked mushroom powder. The prepared solution was left to sit for 72 hours, with periodic shaking to ensure efficient extraction of the mushroom's active ingredients. This was later filtered via a funnel and cotton wool. The filtrate was then dumped, weighed, and used to create the various concentrations for the experiment.

**3.****4 Preparation of NMU**

1g of Nitroso-methyl Urea (NMU) was measured and diluted with 20ml of saline to provide 50mg/ml of NMU, which was then dispensed into a universal bottle. Following five days of acclimatization, the mice were given 50mg/kg-1 body weight of NMU. The NMU solution was administered intra-peritoneally in the animal's ventral midline (between the third and fourth pairs of mammary glands), as described by (Adeboye et al., 2025). Mice were allowed to remain inside for 7 days after the drug was produced in order for it to take effect before treatment began.

**3.5 Mortality and Clinical Signs**

The physiology and behavior of the mice were closely monitored to assess any possible changes or notable differences. These observations (weight log. discoloration of the skin or hair loss) provided insight on the effect of the drugs being administered to each group, dietary disturbance, or environmental stress. The mortality rate was monitored as it pointed towards the level of toxicity of the mutagen (NMU). The rate of mortality was evaluated to determine whether the extract had any contributing lethal effects on the animals relative to that of the mutagen (NMU).

Hence, appropriate care was taken to observe and document any fatalities that occurred during the 60-day treatment period. Any clinical symptoms that emerged during the treatment period were also monitored and recorded. The clinical symptoms observed in the animals were determined by looking at physical changes such as changes in behavior, movement, color, and appetite.

**3.6 Animal Sacrifice**

At the end of the 9-week experimental period following NMU induction and _Pleurotus ostreatus_ extract treatment, all mice were humanely euthanized by cervical dislocation under light diethyl ether anesthesia in the animal house of the Department of Cell Biology and Genetics, University of Lagos. Prior to sacrifice, animals were weighed, and all necessary equipment was prepared to ensure efficient tissue collection. Blood samples were taken via jugular vein puncture and promptly transferred into EDTA bottles for biochemical examination of kidney function markers (MDA, SOD, CAT, GSH, GPx), as well as heparinized bottles for prospective hematological tests. The kidneys were taken, thoroughly dissected, cleaned in 0.9% saline, and stored for histological examination with hematoxylin-eosin staining to determine NMU-induced renal damage and extract-mediated protection.

**3.7 Antioxidants Procedures for Catalase, Sod, Mda, Gsh, Gpx and Protein**

Exactly 0.5g of the tissue was homogenized using tissue homogenizer in 4.5ml of 0.4M sodium phosphate buffer (pH 7.0), centrifuge at 3500rpm for 10min and the supernatant removed for the assay.

**3.7.1 Determination of catalase activity**

Catalase (CAT) was assayed colourimetrically at 620nm and expressed as moles of hydrogen peroxide (H2O2) consumed/min/mg protein as described by Quinlan et al (1994). The reaction mixture (1.5ml) contained 1.0ml of 0.01M pH 7.0 phosphate buffer, 0.1ml of Plasma and 0.4ml of 2M H2O2. The reaction was stopped by the addition of 2.0ml of dichromate-acetic acid reagent (5% potassium dichromate and glacial acetic acid were mixed in 1:3 ratio).

**3.7.2 Determination of SOD activity.**

Total SOD activity in tissue homogenates was determined following the procedure of Marklund and Marklund with some modifications. The method is based on the ability of SOD to inhibit the autoxidation of pyrogallol. In 970 μL of buffer (100mMTris-HCl, 1mM EDTA, pH 8.2), 10μL of homogenates and 20μLpyrogallol(13Mm) were mixed. Assay was performed in thermostated cuvettes at 25°C and changes of absorption were recorded by a spectrophotometer at 480nm. One unit of SOD activity was defined as the amount of enzyme can inhibit the auto-oxidation of 50% the total pyrogallol in the reaction.

**3.7.3** **Measurement of lipid peroxidation products (MDA)**

The assay for membrane lipid peroxidation was done by the method of (Wright et al., 2003) with some modifications. The reaction mixture in a total volume of 2.1 ml contained 0.1 ml sample, 2.0 ml of (TCA 15%, TBA 0.37% and 0.25N HCl in ratio 1:1:1). All the test tubes were placed in a boiling water bath for a period of 15 minute. The tubes were allowed to cool and then centrifuged at 2500×g for 10minute. The amount of malondialdehyde (MDA) formed in each of the samples was assessed by measuring the optical density of the supernatant at 535 nm. The results were expressed as the nmol MDA formed/gram tissue by using a molar extinction coefficient of 1.56×105 M−1 cm−1.

**3.7.4 Determination of Glutathione Peroxidase (Gpx)**

Glutathione peroxidase (GPx) activity was measured by the addition of 0.2ml of 0.4M phosphate buffer pH 7.0, 0.1ml of 10mM sodium oxide, 0.2ml of plasma, 0.2ml of glutathione salt (GSH) and 0.1ml of 0.2mM H202. The mixture was incubated at 37oC for 10mins. The reaction was arrested by 0.4ml of 10% TCA, and centrifuged. The supernatant was assayed for glutathione content by using Ellman's reagent.

**3.7.5 Determination of Reduced Glutathione (GSH)**

Reduced glutathione (GSH) was determined by the method of Ellman G.L (1959). To the homogenate added 10% TCA (equal volume) and centrifuged. 1.0 ml of supernatant was treated with 0.5 ml of Ellmans reagent (19.8 mg of 5, 5'-dithiobisnitro benzoic acid (DTNB) in 100 ml of 0.1% sodium nitrate) and 3.0 ml of phosphate buffer (0.2M, pH 8.0). The absorbance was read at 412 nm.

**3.7.6 Determination of Total protein (Biuret methods)**

Principle: Protein molecules are composed of amino acids arranged in long chains called peptide chains. The links which join the amino acids together are known as peptide bonds. In the Biuret reaction, the cupric ions in the reagent join with the peptide bonds of the protein molecules in an alkaline solution to form a blue-violet coloured complex

Biuret Test Procedure: For each sample, pipette into test tubes 1.0ml of biuret reagent (test) and 1.0ml of blank reagent (reagent blank). Add 0.02ml (20µl) of each sample to the test and 20µl water to the blank. A standard test tube is also set up for each batch and contains 20 µl of standard protein 1.0ml of biuret reagent. Mix and allow to stand at room temperature for 30 minutes or 10 mins at 37oC. Zero the instrument with the reagent blank solution. Measure the absorbance of the test and the standard at 546nm wavelength.

**3.8 Statistics Analysis**

The statistical analyses were performed using Microsoft Excel and reported as mean ± SEM. A Student's t-test was used to compare treatment groups with controls. Differences were considered statistically significant based on p-values derived with Microsoft Excel.

**CHAPTER FOUR**

**RESULTS**

**4.1 Effect of _Pleurotus ostreatus_ Extract on Body Weight of _Mus musculus_**

The body weight of mice across the nine-week experimental period for all treatment groups and the control is presented in Table 6. Mice treated with _Pleurotus ostreatus_ extract at 400 mg kg<sup>\-1</sup> showed a steady and progressive increase in body weight throughout the study, with several weeks exhibiting markedly higher values compared with the control group. The increase in this group was consistently greater than in all other treatments, indicating a strong treatment effect at this dose. Animals administered 200 mg kg<sup>\-1</sup> of the extract also demonstrated gradual weight gain over the experimental period. Although the increase was less pronounced than that of the 400 mg kg<sup>\-1</sup> group, several weeks still showed moderate increases compared with the control, suggesting a dose-dependent response. Mice treated with cisplatin displayed a different pattern, showing mild increases in body weight at some points during the study. These changes were less consistent and generally lower than those observed in the extract-treated groups. Only a few weeks showed noticeable differences from the control group, reflecting the expected impact of cisplatin treatment on general physiological condition. The control group showed a normal pattern of gradual weight increase during the study, with no abrupt shifts. Overall, the highest weight gain was observed in mice treated with 400 mg kg<sup>\-1</sup>, followed by those treated with 200 mg kg<sup>\-1</sup>. The cisplatin group exhibited slight but inconsistent changes, while the control maintained regular growth. These findings indicate that _Pleurotus ostreatus_ extract, particularly at higher doses, contributed to an improvement in body weight compared with the control and cisplatin-treated animals.

**CHAPTER FIVE**

**DISCUSSION**

A key indicator of how well a medicinal herb lessens the toxicity brought on by a certain cytotoxic drug is body weight (Kim et al., 2016). Changes in body weight can offer concrete proof of the extract's ability to mitigate the harmful effects (Kola et al., 2023). When evaluating the negative effects of therapies, drugs, or dangerous substances, body weight is an important consideration. One of the first important indicators of toxicity may be weight variation (Oloyede et al., 2020). In toxicological experiments, evaluating animal development using the weight index is standard practice because it helps interpret compound-related effects (Oloyede et al., 2020).

The present findings indicate that _Pleurotus ostreatus_ ethanolic extract exerts a measurable protective effect in NMU‑induced _Mus musculus_, both at the systemic and renal levels. Mice treated with 400 mg kg⁻¹ of the extract showed the most pronounced and sustained increase in body weight over the nine‑week period, while those given 200 mg kg⁻¹ also exhibited a consistent, though less marked, weight gain relative to the control group. This pattern suggests that _Pleurotus ostreatus_ alleviated NMU‑associated toxicity and supported better overall physiological status, likely through improved metabolic efficiency and attenuation of oxidative and inflammatory stress, as has been reported for oyster mushroom and other edible fungi in experimental models (Ferreira et al., 2020; Jayachandran et al., 2022). In contrast, the cisplatin group, despite some transient increases, displayed less stable weight progression, consistent with the catabolic and cachectic effects of cytotoxic agents on rapidly dividing tissues and energy balance (Kocełak et al., 2021). The superior weight profile in the 400 mg kg⁻¹ group therefore points to a dose‑dependent benefit of _Pleurotus ostreatus_ in maintaining growth and general condition under carcinogen challenge, in line with earlier work showing that mushroom supplementation improves performance and resilience in animals exposed to toxic or stressful conditions (Elsayed et al., 2015; Jayachandran et al., 2022).

The kidney antioxidant profile provides mechanistic support for this systemic protection. Total protein content was slightly higher in the high‑dose _Pleurotus_ group than in the control, suggesting better preservation of renal tissue integrity and protein homeostasis under NMU stress. Similar modest improvements in tissue protein levels have been observed in nephrotoxic models treated with _Pleurotus_ extracts and are often attributed to reduced protein oxidation and stabilization of cellular membranes (El‑Sayed et al., 2020; Elkhateeb et al., 2024). Catalase activity, although reduced across all NMU‑exposed groups, was relatively better preserved in the 200 mg kg⁻¹ extract group than in the cisplatin group, indicating that _Pleurotus ostreatus_ partially maintained enzymatic detoxification of hydrogen peroxide. This is consistent with reports that _Pleurotus spp._ counteract xenobiotic‑induced oxidative stress by enhancing or normalizing catalase and related enzymes in renal and hepatic tissues (El‑Sayed et al., 2020; Jayachandran et al., 2022). These trends suggest that the extract did not completely normalize antioxidant enzyme activity but attenuated the degree of NMU‑induced disruption.

Superoxide dismutase activity was lower in all treatment groups compared with the control, with the most marked reductions seen in the 400 mg kg⁻¹ _Pleurotus_ and cisplatin groups. Decreased SOD in this context likely reflects persistent oxidative burden and consumption of the enzyme in the dismutation of superoxide radicals, a phenomenon also documented in other carcinogen‑ and drug‑induced nephrotoxicity models (Kangari et al., 2018; Kocełak et al., 2021). The inability of _Pleurotus ostreatus_ to fully restore SOD suggests that certain reactive oxygen species pathways remain active despite treatment, and that the extract's primary impact may lie more in limiting downstream lipid peroxidation and preserving glutathione‑dependent systems than in completely reversing superoxide‑related perturbations. This selective modulation of antioxidant defenses is compatible with evidence that mushroom‑derived polysaccharides and phenolics exert differential effects on the various components of the redox network rather than uniformly elevating all enzymes (Elkhateeb et al., 2024; Jayachandran et al., 2022).

Malondialdehyde levels, used as an index of lipid peroxidation, were lowest in the 400 mg kg⁻¹ _Pleurotus_ group and slightly reduced in the 200 mg kg⁻¹ group when compared with the NMU control and cisplatin groups. This pattern indicates that _Pleurotus ostreatus_ effectively limited peroxidative damage to membrane lipids, which is critical given that excessive MDA production has been linked to mutagenesis, impaired cell function, and tumor promotion (Kangari et al., 2018). The stronger reduction at the higher dose underscores a dose‑responsive antioxidant effect and is consistent with studies showing that _Pleurotus_ extracts significantly lower renal and hepatic MDA in animals exposed to heavy metals, ethylene glycol, and other nephrotoxic insults, largely attributed to ergothioneine, β‑glucans, and phenolic constituents with strong radical‑scavenging capacity (El‑Sayed et al., 2020; Elkhateeb et al., 2024; Jayachandran et al., 2022). By attenuating lipid peroxidation, the extract likely contributes to maintaining membrane integrity, ion transport, and mitochondrial function in NMU‑challenged kidneys.

The glutathione system showed partial but important preservation in extract‑treated animals. Reduced glutathione concentrations remained lower than in the distilled water control but were less depleted in the _Pleurotus_ groups than would be expected under sustained oxidative stress, indicating that the extract helped conserve intracellular thiol reserves. Glutathione peroxidase activity, while not fully restored, remained relatively close to control values across all groups, with only modest inter‑group variation. Together, these observations suggest that the GSH/GPx axis retained functional activity in the presence of _Pleurotus ostreatus_, enabling continued detoxification of peroxides even when upstream enzymes such as SOD and CAT were compromised. Previous work has shown that _Pleurotus_ supplementation can elevate or maintain GSH and GPx in renal and hepatic tissues during exposure to cadmium, urolithiasis‑inducing agents, and hyperoxaluria, through mechanisms involving Nrf2 activation, improved cysteine availability, and reduced oxidant load (El‑Sayed et al., 2020; Elkhateeb et al., 2024).

Integrating these findings, _Pleurotus ostreatus_ appears to confer multi‑level protection against NMU‑induced toxicity in _Mus musculus_, improving body weight trajectories, reducing lipid peroxidation, and partially stabilizing key antioxidant systems in the kidney. The benefits are most evident at 400 mg kg⁻¹, which yielded the greatest weight gain and the lowest MDA levels, supporting a dose‑dependent relationship between extract intake and renoprotective efficacy. These outcomes are compatible with the broader view of _Pleurotus spp._ as functional foods rich in polysaccharides, phenolics, and ergothioneine that exert antioxidant, anti‑inflammatory, and cytoprotective effects across multiple organ systems (Ferreira et al., 2020; Jayachandran et al., 2022). At the same time, the incomplete normalization of SOD and CAT underscores that NMU‑induced oxidative stress is only partially countered by the extract and that additional strategies such as longer treatment duration, combined antioxidant therapy, or targeting specific signaling pathways like NF‑κB and p53 may be required for full restoration of redox balance (El‑Sayed et al., 2020; Kangari et al., 2018). Overall, the findings suggest _Pleurotus ostreatus'_ potential as an adjuvant therapy in situations defined by oxidative kidney injury and nephrotoxic chemical exposure, necessitating additional scientific and translational research.

**5.1 CONCLUSION**

The study shows that _Pleurotus ostreatus_ ethanolic extract, especially at 400 mg kg⁻¹, ameliorated NMU‑induced toxicity in _Mus musculus_ by improving body weight and supporting overall physiological status. Kidney antioxidant assessment indicates that the extract reduced lipid peroxidation, as reflected by lower MDA levels, and partially preserved glutathione and glutathione‑dependent defenses while moderating the decline in key enzymes such as CAT and SOD. These biochemical changes are consistent with a nephroprotective, antioxidant effect rather than complete normalization of oxidative stress markers. Together, the systemic and renal outcomes suggest a dose‑dependent protective role for _Pleurotus ostreatus_ against NMU‑mediated oxidative damage. The findings support its potential as an adjuvant in conditions involving oxidative kidney injury and justify further scientific and translational research.
